the AAU’s president and nine other univer-
sity chancellors and presidents. Along with
advocating improved care of the mentally
ill and increased accountability on the part
of media for their portrayals of violence, the
statement calls for the tightening of certain
gun—control laws.

“Many high-powered weapons that have
no legitimate use for hunting, marksmanship,
or self-defense continue to be bought and sold,
as are the high—volume magazines often used
by mass murderers,” the statement reads.

But the National Riﬂe Association, which
advocates against such legislation, has claimed
that more citizens carrying ﬁrearms prevents
such mass violence. The NRA released a state-
ment to that effect on Dec. 21, criticizing “gun-
free zones” at schools.

In line with the NRA’s long—held stance,
some states’ laws mandate allowing ﬁrearms
on university campuses.

Sgt. Aaron Chapin, a spokesman for the

University of Wisconsin-Madison Police De-
partment, explained that Wisconsin’s con-
cealed-carry law, which took effect in_No-
vember 2011, explicitly allows for weapons
on university campuses.

But under the law, he said, the university
can still ban weapons inside its buildings as
long as it posts signs to that effect at entrances.

Chapin said that he knew of no gun vio-
lence having taken place on campus since
the law took effect. He could think of one in-
dividual who was reported to the department
because he brought a gun indoors.

Chapin said that though the individual held
a concealed- carry permit, the person received
a citation for trespassing under Wisconsin
state law.

He also explained that UW attempted to
receive an exception from the 2011 concealed-
carry law.

“Our department’s stance and the uni-
versity’s stance is that having a whole lot of
weapons out there doesn’t necessarily prevent
[gun violence],” he said.

But groups that argue for lessening restric-
tions on owning and carrying ﬁrearms say that

legally owned weapons protect innocent lives.
Like the NRA, the advocacy group Stu-
dents for Concealed Carry argues thatﬁrearms

in the right hands enable citizens to defend ,

themselves.

Reid Smith, Students for Concealed Carry’s
director of development, criticized gun-free
zones in ajan. 8 statement he published on
the’organization’s website. In it,- he argued
that violent criminals cannot be expected
to abide bylaws that restrict where they can
carry ﬁrearms.

Smith added that even those who support
gun-free zones admit that “such policies don’t

_keep the ‘bad guys with guns’ out, but they’re
‘still too afraid of the ‘good guys with guns’ to
abolish the zones.”

He went on to call such restrictions, which
he believes only law—abiding citizens would
follow, “ironic.”

Neither the NRA nor Students for Con-
cealed Carry responded to multiple requests
for comment made over the span of several
days.

Some have expressed concerns that armed
citizens, even law—abiding ones, may not pre-

vent mass shootings or minimize the resulting
casualties.
Chief Bob Roberts of the West Virginia

University Police Department said that he i

had read statistics derived from shootouts
involving trained law enforcement oﬂ'lcers',
including FBI agents, that indicated an average
of only three out of every 10 shots the officers
ﬁred hit the intended target.

“That means there’s seven that miss,” he
said.

He believed that such ﬁgures pointed to the
possibility that even legally armed citizens at
the scene of a shooting might increase the risk
of additional casualties among bystanders.

Roberts said that like _Pennsylvan.ia’s laws,
West Virginia’s laws leave the choice of wheth-
er to ban or allow ﬁrearms on private property
up to those who own that property, and WVU
chooses to ban them on its campus.

Roberts also explained that more guns on
the scenes of such “stressﬁil situations” pres-
ent another problem for law enforcement.

“When police officers show up at a scene
and there’s ﬁrearms, we don’t know who the
bad guys are,” Roberts said. I

