MEN’S BASKETBALL

Nate Barnes
Senior Staff I/Vriter

The Pitt men’s basketball team (13-4,
1-3 Big East) travels to the Philadel-
phia area Wednesday evening to take
on cross-state rival Villanova (11-5,
2-1 Big East), as the Panthers hope
to return to theirwinning ways after
a disappointing 1-3 start to confer-
ence play. 1

Looking ahead to Wednesday’s
game, Pitt head coach Jamie Dixon
explained the key to his team’s suc-
cess will be nothing new or extraor-
dinary — Pitt just needs to‘ rebound
better.

“We’ll need to get back to re-
bound,” Dixon said. “That’s what
I’ve been saying all year, and it’s cost
us those last couple games that we
lost. And in the win against George-
town, we out-rebounded them, so
the numbers don’t lie.”

In addition to Dixon, junior
guard Trey Zeigler also knows the
importance of out-rebounding the
opposition and the success that ac-
complishing such an objective will
likely lead to for the Panthers.

“Obviously, we got beat on the
boards again [against Marquette],”
Zeigler said. “All three games we
lost, we lost on the boards. Coach
has been emphasizing that, and we
deﬁnitely can play better defense.”

Redshirt senior point guard Tray
Woodall should also be back in the
lineup Wednesday night at The Pa-
vilion after suffering a concussion
during a loose-ball scrum Saturday
afternoon against Marquette that

SPORTS

Panthers focus on rebounding before matchup with Villanova

kept him out for the remainder of
the overtime defeat.

“It’s 24 hours, no symptoms.
Then you have some conditioning,
some running in the 24 hours after
that,” Dixon said. “If the doctors feel
that he can play, then he will play.”

“I’m ﬁne,” Woodall responded
when prompted about the status of
his concussion. And when asked if
he would play Wednesday, Woodall
simply gave a “yup.”

Likely starting at the point,
Woodall will have great defensive
responsibility on the perimeter as
Villanova’s offense ﬂows through
its guards.

Woodall said Pitt defenders must
keep their man in front of them if
they hope to defend successfully
against the Wildcats.

“Just contain the dribbler. It’s the
same dribble—drive offense. We just
gotta make sure we keep the ball in
front of us and try to make sure we
attack the glass,” Woodall said.

Additionally, Dixon recognizes
the ability of the Wildcats — who are
coming off a 72-61 loss at Syracuse
- to knock down the 3-point shot
